# Security Rule — Mandatory Constraints

Security is not optional. All generated code must follow these constraints.

## Tenant isolation
- All resources must be tenant-aware
- Never mix tenant data implicitly
- Every persisted business object must include tenant/org ownership
- Authorization must be enforced server-side

## Secrets
- Never store secrets in plain project JSON
- Never commit secrets to source control
- Use secret references instead of raw values where possible
- Mask sensitive values in logs, errors, and UI responses

## Kubernetes workloads
- Use non-root containers by default
- Apply CPU/memory requests and limits
- Prefer read-only root filesystem when possible
- Avoid privileged containers
- Avoid host mounts unless explicitly approved
- Use dedicated service accounts with minimal permissions

## OpenClaw integration
- Assume OpenClaw is local-only by default
- Do not expose raw local gateways publicly
- Require token/auth handshake for local integration
- Dangerous tools must be opt-in only
- Any shell/file/network capability must be treated as high-risk

## Logging
- Never log tokens, passwords, API keys, raw credentials, or sensitive payloads
- Truncate or mask sensitive request/response data

## Input handling
- Validate all input at service boundaries
- Reject malformed input early
- Use schema validation for external payloads

## Prohibited shortcuts
- No mock auth in production code paths
- No hardcoded secrets
- No wildcard CORS in protected services
- No "temporary" bypasses without explicit TODO and explanation
